The paper discusses the success and vulnerability of modern AI technologies, which are typically studied in the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), computer security and cryptography (cs.CR), and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE). The focus on learning non-linear functional dependencies from high-dimensional data sets suggests a strong connection to machine learning and artificial intelligence, while the discussion of adversarial attacks and robustness points towards computer security and cryptography. The mention of data sets also suggests a connection to computer vision, and the use of high-dimensional data sets suggests a potential connection to neural and evolutionary computing.
